Introduction¶

Phase 1 Summary¶

This project (as the title states) intends to predict who would subscribe for a term deposit by using the various descriptive features at-hand. The data-set used for the purpose of the entire project has been sourced from the UCI Machine Learning Repository (Bank Marketing Data Set, 2014). The information contained in the dataset is about the clients of a Portuguese Bank, dated from May 2008 to November 2010.

In Phase 1: Data Preparation & Visualization, we defined our descriptive features, and the target feature term_deposit. This phase was related to the Data Preprocessing of the data-set. The data-set did contain certain missing values denoted as unknown in features such as education, housing, loan, marital, default, job which were removed citing that their contribution was almost negligible. The data-set happened to contain 10 duplicate observations which were also removed as they would serve no value for the purposes of Predictive Modelling. Furthermore, a descriptive feature titled duration implying the duration of the call that the customer representative of the bank had with the client was not considered as part of the final data-frame as the whole purpose of Predictive Modelling is to provide knowledge as to who would be worth contacting, and hence preventing expenditure. Finally, we went on to rename certain columns appropriately, and we also renamed the target feature which was denoted as y to term_deposit.

The second part of the Phase-1 report was to perform Exploratory Data Analysis and Visualization using the pre-processed data-set. We performed Univariate, Bi-variate analysis along with three-variable plots. We found that the problem at-hand is a highly imbalanced one, and that would make sense as it is a marketing campaign. Other observations included that most of the clients were employed as admins, and that most of the clients held a university degree. The majority of the clients ranged between the age of 30 and 40, and almost 85% of the clients were being contacted for the first-time. Our data-set included some social and economic features as well, and they had a role to play in the outcome of the target variable, for instance, the cons_price_idx shared a reverse relationship with term_deposit, and as the emp_var_rate decreased, more people subscribed for a term deposit at the bank. A point that was evident that as the euribor3m reduced over-time, so did the cons_conf_idx, and hence reduced the term_deposit subscription.

The work done in Phase-1 was the foundation stone for the tasks that are to be done in this report (Phase-2). Before starting to predict anything, we need to be aware of what we are dealing with. Doing the Data Wrangling Process helps to remove all the unnecessary data from the data-set which would have during the modelling section only increased computational time and a possibly false prediction model to be deployed. Not to mention that during the feature-selection process duration would have easily come up in the top-10 features because having duration adds no-value to the task of predictive modelling, as we intend to find-out who are the clients that are worth contacting by the bank. Furthermore, duplicate observations in the data-set as stated earlier would not provide any benefit for predictive modelling. Hence, the tasks performed in Phase-1 were of paramount importance to what is supposed to be done in this report.

Note: From the data preparation stage, tasks such as One-Hot-Encoding (or Integer-Encoding), Scaling and Sampling will be performed in this report.

Report Overview¶

The main aim of this project is to predict who will subscribe for a term deposit at the bank in question, and we will be doing so by fitting and comparing different classifiers. So far our data-set contains 10 nominal categorical features (day_of_week, month, default, housing,loan, job, marital_status, education, contact, and poutcome), and 9 numeric features (p_days, age, campaign, previous, emp_var_rate, cons_price_idx, cons_conf_idx, euribor3m, and nr_employed). Our target feature term_deposit has two classes namely "yes" and "no".

This phase would proceed with converting the categorical features to numeric which would internally involve encoding of nominal descriptive features. For the nominal categorical features, we will follow the One-Hot-Encoding process. After having encoded all the descriptive features, we will encode the target feature, considering the "yes" outcome to be the positive class. One of the most crucial parts before modelling is that of "Scaling" the features. Scaling or Normalization becomes important as the observations in the descriptive features might take different range of values, and hence impacting the predicting power of the model. We will be performing the "Min-Max Scaling".

Concluding to the completion of the above tasks, we then proceed towards core predictive modelling techniques specifically "Feature Selection" for a start. This is an important step as in the real-world scenario using all the descriptive features to predict a particular outcome would increase the computational time of the task and prone our models to overfitting, and hence we will identify the top-10 features using the Random Forest Importance and the F-Score method. After which, we will be sampling our data to 5000 observations considering the processing limitations of this machine. We then split our data into test and train following a 70:30 split ratio. Furthermore, we move on to "Model Fitting and Tuning" through which we will be finding the ideal hyperparameters for each algorithm that we will be using along with a particular set of features. The scoring metric for each algorithm would be roc_auc as this is a binary classification problem, moreover, a highly imbalanced on as well. As an additional task, we will also be fitting a neural network algorithm into our sampled data-set including the fine-tuning of 5 different Neural Network Hyperparameters. The final step of the predictive modelling includes "Model Comparison", we will be calculating the AUC Scores via the cross_val_score method using paired t-tests, and find out the best performing algorithm, along with other criteria such as confusion matrices and classification reports.

The next section "Critique and Limitations" would include the limitations of the approach we have followed, at the same-time providing possible solutions to drawbacks. "Summary and Conclusions" would include the summary of the entire project report i.e. Phase 1 and Phase 2, followed by our findings from having performed on this data-set. And in the "Conclusions" section, we will reflect back to our goals and objectives with the end-result of this report.

Note: Before beginning to work with any sklearn modules, we will convert our pandas data-frame to a numpy array.

Overview of Methodology¶

Our journey to effectively selecting the correct model of our problem, would begin with the encoding of the categorical features, and since this is a classification problem, our target feature term_deposit is also a categorical feature. We would encode our target feature after splitting our main data-set into one for descriptive features, and the other for the target feature. Following which, all the descriptive features with only 2 levels, would be encoded with only one binary variable using the pandas function of get_dummies(), and normally for other categorical features. We will then 'Scale' our data, as to normalise it. The scaling would be done only on the descriptive features data-set. Before the scaling is performed, we will save our original data-set to preserve the column names, as the output of the MinMaxScaler function is a numpy array. We will then proceed towards core predictive modelling, beginning with Feature Selection.

In Feature Selection, we would ideally be trying to find out the best 10 features using the Random Forest Importance method and the F-Score method, we won't be using these 10 feature through out the modelling stage, since we intend to tune the hyperparameters of a specific algorithm using different set of features. We then proceed towards the Model Fitting and Tuning stage, where-in, we will work with four different algorithms, namely, K-Nearest Neighbors, Decision Tree, Naive Bayes, and Logistic Regressor and tune their hyperparameters via their respective classifier, and by using the custom sourced class RFISelector() as part of the pipeline. We will be performing a GridSearch approach using a 5 Fold Cross Validation technique without any repetitions using roc_auc as the scoring metric. After which, we will also have a look at how each algorithm performs on the test data.

We will also undertake an additional task of Neural Network Model Fitting and Tuning, during which, we will try to tune 7 hyperparameters.

The final stage of the predictive modelling process would be the Model Comparison. In it, we will be comparing the performance of our models using thier cross validation scores on the test data. We will draw conclusions by conducting a paired t-test (by keeping the same random state through-out for each model), to know if the difference between the performance of the various combination of models is statistically significant or not.

We will also reflect back to our problem at-hand, and make the final call as to which model is to be picked for deployment based on the classification report and the confusion matrix.

Scaling Features¶

An important step before moving towards the modelling section is that of "Normalizing" the data-set. It is crucial as some observations may contain different variance as compared to others in the data-set, and hence, the predicting power or the actual prediction may come out to be False. For the purpose of this project, we will be using the Min-Max Scaling method.

Note: Since this scaling method uses a fit_transform whose output is a numpy array due to which the column names will be lost, hence we will keep a copy of our original data-frame before-hand.

Predictive Modelling¶

Feature Selection¶

One of the most important steps in the concepts of Machine Learning. We will work with the top 10 features only as with the complete set of features, we might run into the problem of overfitting. Having stated that, in the Model Fitting and Tuning stage, we will work with different hyper-parameter for each algorithm against specific number of features.

We would be performing the Feature Selection and Ranking using:

1. Random Forest Importance (Filter Method)
2. F-Score (Filter Method)

Before we proceed, we will convert our target feature term_deposit into a numpy array as well for working with sklearn modules.

In [ ]:
# Converting our target feature to a numpy array as well
target = target.values

I. Random Forest Importance¶

For the first, feature-selection and ranking, we will work with the Random Forest Importance which is essentially a filter-based method.

1. KNN Hyperparameter Tuning and Visualization¶

For K-Nearest Neighbors Algorithm there are two hyperparameters namely k (number of neighbors) and p (type of distance metric). But, for this and for the following algorithms, we will also fine tune the number of features along with the hyperparameters. Earlier, we performed feature selection using Random Forest Importance and F-Score, similarly, we will do the same for the fine tuning process by passing the Random Forest Importance (we could also use SelectKBest() ) as a function under steps of a Pipeline.

We will be performing the below steps using 100 estimators. Additionally, the same would be used for the Decision Tree Classifier Algorithm, the Naive Bayes Algorithm, and on the Logistic Regressor as well.

Being a classification problem, and that too a binary one, we will use the scoring metric as roc_auc , because the problem at-hand is a highly imbalanced one. Alternatively, we could have also used class weights as a step in the pipeline to counter the imbalance.

Note: The following function is sourced from the Practice SK5 Solutions tutorial (Akman, 2022).

In [ ]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from numpy import argsort

# Creating a class for the Random Forest Classifier
class RFIFeatureSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    
    # Defining Constructors of the class
    def __init__(self, n_features_=10):
        self.n_features_ = n_features_
        self.fs_indices_ = None
        self.fs_importance_ = None
        
    # This overrides the 'fit' function
    def fit(self, X, y):
        model_rfi = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=999)
        model_rfi.fit(X, y)
        self.fs_indices_ = argsort(model_rfi.feature_importances_)[::-1][0:self.n_features_] 
        self.fs_importance_ = model_rfi.feature_importances_[self.fs_indices_ ]
        return self 
    
    # This overrides the 'transform' function
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        return X[:, self.fs_indices_]

We will now implement our Pipeline for the K-Nearest Neighbor Algorithm. The above class is being called through the steps of the Pipeline. We are also considering parallel processing via the usage of the argument n_jobs = -2 in the GridSearchCV function.

Note: The total number of combinations would be 4 x 5 x 4 = 80 combinations.

In [ ]:
# Declaring the Pipeline

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

pipe_KNN = Pipeline(steps=[('rfi_fs', RFIFeatureSelector()), #Call to the custom sourced function 
                           ('knn', KNeighborsClassifier())])

params_pipe_KNN = {'rfi_fs__n_features_': [10, 20, 30, data.shape[1]],
                   'knn__n_neighbors': [1, 5, 10, 15, 20],
                   'knn__p': [1, 2, 3, 4]}

                           scoring='roc_auc',
                           verbose=1)

In [ ]:
# Custom Function to get search results as a Pandas Data-frame

def get_search_results(gs):
    def model_result(scores, params):
        scores = {'mean_score': np.mean(scores),
             'std_score': np.std(scores), #Returns Standard Deviation
             'min_score': np.min(scores), #Returns the Minimum Score 
             'max_score': np.max(scores)} #Returns the Maximum Score
        return pd.Series({**params,**scores})
    
    models = [] #Creating an empty list for the different models
    scores = [] #Creating an empty list for storing scores of different models
    
    for i in range(gs.n_splits_):
        key = f"split{i}_test_score"
        r = gs.cv_results_[key]        
        scores.append(r.reshape(-1,1))
    all_scores = np.hstack(scores)
    
    for p, s in zip(gs.cv_results_['params'], all_scores):
        models.append((model_result(s, p)))
    
    pipe_results = pd.concat(models, axis=1).T.sort_values(['mean_score'], ascending=False)
    columns_first = ['mean_score', 'std_score', 'max_score', 'min_score']
    columns = columns_first + [c for c in pipe_results.columns if c not in columns_first]
    
    return pipe_results[columns]

3. Gaussian Naive Bayes Hyperparameter Tuning and Visualization¶

One of the requirements of the Naive Bayes Algorithm is that it requires the features to have a normal distribution which usually is not the case, and to make valid that condition, we take the help of a power transformer, which is applied on the input data before we "fit" the model.

In [ ]:
# Using the Power Transformer

For the var_smoothing hyperparameter, we will be using the values from 1 to -3 with 80 different values in-between (including extreme values), as the number of fits increases drastically with increased number of values. Model Comparison¶

One of the most important steps in Machine Learning is the Model Comparison, ideally, because we want to find out the "Best" model for our needs, and also how the model will perform when deployed. But, there are two major considerations to keep in mind for evaluation; how the data is split, and what metric is to be used for evalutaion ?

In our case (as performed above), we had used a 5-Fold Cross Validation process and deployed it to each of our algorithms. Regarding what metric is to be used, we had used the scoring metric as roc_auc, because the problem at-hand is a classification problem, the target-feature is binary, and we have a class-imbalance to tackle as well. Therefore, roc_auc is the perfect fit for this type of a problem.

To find out the best model, we will use the paired t-test statistical test. Before doing so, we need to see the performance evaluation of our algorithms via the cross_val_score , but this time, we will use 5 fold cross validation with 2 repetitions on each tuned classifiers. After which, we shall conduct the statistical significance test on the following combinations:

  1. KNN v. DT,
  2. KNN v. NB,
  3. KNN v. LR,
  4. DT v. NB,
  5. DT v. LR, and
  6. NB v. LR

Now, we will calculate the mean cross_val_scorefor each Classifier using their respective best estimator.

In [ ]:
# Importing necessary packages

                                 X=d_test,

Comparing the above 4 mean cross validation scores (roc_auc), we can observe that Logistic Regressor outperforms the other algorithms. But, a point to be noted is that the difference between the other values for the Logistic Regressor is very small. The score for the Logistic Regressor is 0.819 approximately, while for KNN it is 0.804, for Decision Tree, we obtained a score of 0.788, and via Naive Bayes, a score of 0.811 was obtained as well.

For this very reason, we need to conduct a statistical test to know if the difference between the values is statistically significant or not i.e. can we reject our Null Hypothesis ?

In [ ]:
# Conducting the t-tests
from scipy import stats

print(f't-test: KNN v. DT: {stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_KNN, cv_results_DT)}')
print(f't-test: KNN v. NB: {stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_KNN, cv_results_NB)}')
print(f't-test: KNN v. LR: {stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_KNN, cv_results_LR)}')
print(f't-test: DT v. NB: {stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_DT, cv_results_NB)}')
print(f't-test: DT v. LR: {stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_DT, cv_results_LR)}')
print(f't-test: NB v. LR: {stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_NB, cv_results_LR)}')

t-test: KNN v. DT: Ttest_relResult(statistic=2.012844187808225, pvalue=0.07498312650974139)
t-test: KNN v. NB: Ttest_relResult(statistic=-1.2305523155442175, pvalue=0.249681310621311)
t-test: KNN v. LR: Ttest_relResult(statistic=-2.7241729060734134, pvalue=0.02344710423588045)
t-test: DT v. NB: Ttest_relResult(statistic=-2.177772877389573, pvalue=0.057382325273147246)
t-test: DT v. LR: Ttest_relResult(statistic=-4.357207999628388, pvalue=0.0018309029375239707)
t-test: NB v. LR: Ttest_relResult(statistic=-1.0602301624142572, pvalue=0.31666263633210895)

The p-value is of consideration here, if its value is greater than $\alpha$ (significance level = 0.05), then, we deem the conclusion of the test to be as statistically insignificant. In the output of the results above, we can infer that, only two out of the six have a p-value < 0.05, and that is for KNN v. LR, and DT v.LR.

Therefore, we can state that the Logistic Regressor is the best model as it is statistically better than Decision Tree and K-Nearest Neighbors, although, it is not statistically significant when compared with Naive Bayes.

Considering that this data-set is about the plausible clients of the bank who did or did not invest in a term deposit (target feature), we would want to pick out a model, that correctly classifies the people who subscribed for a term deposit, therefore, our ideal metric to look would be recall. Out of all values above, we would ideally pick the one with the maximum value of recall for the class label '1', which would turn out to be the Decision Tree Model, contrary to our paired t-test, which clearly stated that Logistic Regressor was the best model to consider. Another inference that can be made from the above confusion matrix for Logistic Regressor is that, it identified 28 clients to have subscribed, whereas, in actual practice, they did not, and this number is lower than that of a Decision Tree. On the other-hand, we can say that the Decision Tree model identified 68 people who had actually subscribed to a term deposit, and the same parameter is lower for Logistic Regressor with 57. Additionally, the Logistic Regressor had 130 people who had subscribed but our model suggested otherwise.

Taking all the points into consideration, and the quote Machine learning is as much as art as it is science, we can say that although the difference in performance of the Logistic Regressor is statistically significant, but also considering the economics and business practices, a bank wants more clients to be characterized correctly, which is in favour of the Decision Tree Model, and also the fact that, the Logistic Regressor identified true clients as false, which would effectively dampen the performance of the bank.

Therefore, we can state that the Decision Tree would be the best model for the problem at-hand.

Critique and Limitations¶

  1. To begin with, during pre-processing, we did not consider the duration attribute as our main aim was to predict the outcome without having the information of how long the call between the client and bank representative lasted. Alternatively, some might consider this attribute as it has a high influence on the target feature.

  2. We for our predictive analysis considered only 5000 observations, and additionally, we performed only a 5-Fold Cross Validation without any repetitions, for having slightly shorter run-times. However, in an actual practice, we would rarely subset our data, infact, we would prefer training our model on the entire data, with increased number of repetitions. Having said that, since the cross validation method is constant through out, the comparative nature allows us to judge the performance in an unbiased manner.


  3. A definite strength of our models is that, it intends to avoid overfitting by not considering the entire set of features. To some extent, there might be overfitting, but it is definitely much lower than that would have been the case with complete set of features.

  4. Our neural network model hypertuning, computes accuracy instead of roc_auc, because when performed with the latter, the end result is a nan value. Therefore, if the model were to keep track of loss in roc_auc as the model ran, it would have been possible for us to compare it to our other models.

  5. Since by conducting the statistical test, and via the classification matrix, we found that Logistic Regressor was the model for this data-set, we could further improve it by considering additional hyper-parameters such as max_iter, and class_weight.

  6. If we observe constantly, the lowest score in terms of performance on training data, auc score on test data(without cross validation), and the roc_auc score for plotting the ROC Curve, was the lowest for the Naive Bayes model, which may have to do with the power transformation, and from the confusion matrix for the model, we can observe that the 'zero frequency problem' is quite evident for this data-set.

  7. Since the best model turned out to be the Decision Tree, therefore, we could as a further enhancement try to fit the an ensemble such as a Random Forest Classifier, that would provide a better percentage for recall.

Summary and Conclusions¶

I. Project Summary¶

Our project was divided into two phases, therefore, we will divide our summary phase wise for better representation.

PHASE 1

  1. Phase-1 was entirely related to data pre-processing and data visualization. Our pre-processing journey began with the search for missing values, luckily, we did not find any. But, there were certain attributes that contained an unknown label, we dropped them citing their contribution was less as compared to the rest of the dataset. After which, we found 10 duplicate observations in our data-set, those were also dropped, as they are not helpful in the predictive modelling process.

  2. Furthermore, we dropped the duration attribute, as its value cannot be known before a call is placed by the client representative of the bank, therefore, considering this particular attribute would have rendered the predictive modelling process and its outcomes skewed or unfair.

  3. Continuing with phase-1, there were two observations in which the clients were below the age of 17, therefore, they were also dropped because a general adult age is 18, and the bank would not and cannot allow a minor to purchase a term deposit. Few columns were renamed (including the target feature) to better represent their meanings.

  4. After the data wrangling process, we visualized our data to find relationships between attributes. To be specific, we conducted univariate plots, bi-variate plots, and three-variable plots. From them, we infered that 12.7% of the total clients had taken a subscription, majority of the clients were employed as admins, and most of the clients held a university degree. Moreover, majority of the dataset was formed by the clients between the ages of 30 and 40. 96% of the clients were never contacted before.

  5. We observed that as the cons_price_idx (Consumer Price Index) increased the outcome of the target variable term_deposit shifted towards the negative. The preference of people to subscribing a term deposit increased when the emp_var_rate went down. Although, quite contextually evident, we found evidence that as the Euribor3m rate reduced, so did the cons_conf_idx, and hence, the term_deposit went down.

PHASE 2

  1. Phase-2 was entirely related to core predictive modelling techniques. We started with the encoding of the target feature, prior to which our entire data-set was divided into two components, namely, descriptive features data, and the target feature target.

  2. Following which, we encoded the categorical variables using the get_dummies pandas package. The attributes default, housing, loan, and contact had two levels, therefore, we defined only one binary variable for them. Furthermore, the scaling of our descriptive data-set data took place via Min-Max scaling method. We now proceed towards the essential predictive modelling tasks.

  3. We performed 'Feature Selection' to select the top-10 features using the Random Forest Importance and F-Score method, this was done to find out which were the top 10 ranked features, but not necessarily selected to perform predictive modelling.

  4. For the 'Model Fitting and Tuning' task, we subsetted our data-set(s) to include only 5000 observations because of computational limitations. After which, we split our data-set(s) into train and test using the sklearn model train_test_split.

  5. For the hyper-parameter tuning task, we initiated a 5 Fold Cross Validation Method without any repetitions, and this was done via the StratifiedKFold Method. The random_state was set to 999 for reproducibility.

  6. For predictive modelling, we used four algorithms, namely, K-Nearest Neighbors, Decision Tree, Naive Bayes, and Logistic Regressor. The predictive modelling through each algorithm was performed with the use of 'Pipelines', with steps using the custom sourced class RFIFeatureSelector(), and respective Classifier for each algorithm class. We also used 'GridSearchCV' for implementing our cross validation method, and our scoring metric was roc_auc.

  7. After the implementation of each model, we found that the Decision Tree model produced a slightly better roc_auc score (79.83%) than other models on the training data. Moreover, the roc curve was plotted for each model as well.

  8. We then proceeded to the additional task of Neural Network Model Fitting and Tuning, during which, we hypertuned the batch size, epochs, learning rate, momentum, optimizer, activation funtion, and the dropout rate.


  9. Our next stage was Model Comparison, where-in, we performed a paired statistical t-test, after having obtained the cross validation score for each model's best estimator by checking its performance on the test data. The cross_val_score method was performed with 5 folds and 2 repetitions using the RepeatedStratifiedKFold method.

  10. From the cross_val_score, the Logistic Regressor produced the best score of 0.819 outperforming the Decision Tree Model. From the paired t-test, we found statistical evidence that the Logistic Regressor performed better than the Decision Tree Model and the K-Nearest Neighbors model as well. Therefore, as they were the only statistical significant result, we could state that the Logistic Regressor was indeed the best model.

  11. Following the statistical test, we also presented the classification report and the confusion matrices for each model, recall was the factor of consideration, as we are dealing with the customers of a bank, and resources have to be monitored by the bank, but via the confusion matrices, we noticed that the Decision Tree produced a better result in terms of correctly categorizing the customers who had subscribed for a term deposit (recall). Therefore, we opted for Decision Tree for our model deployment.

II. Summary of Findings¶

We used four different algorithms to decide, which would be the ideal fit. The K-Nearest Neighbor algorithm, the Decision Tree, the Naive Bayes, and the Logistic Regressor produced scores of 0.782, 0.798, 0.757, and 0.783 respectively on the training data. On the training data, the Decision Tree model performed the best. The models that selected the entire set of features as their best features were re-run without considering for all the features to avoid any overfitting.The highest cross validation score on the training data was produced by the Decision Tree using the top-10 features selected by Random Forest Importance. The K-NN and the Decision Tree model selected the top 10 features as their best featuers, whereas, the Naive Bayes and the Logistic Regressor selected 30 as their top number of features.

The aucscore on the test-data without any cross-validation were also conducted, through which, also the Decision Tree performed the best with a score of 0.6688, with a close trail by the Logistic Regressor at 0.6417. The roc_auc score calculated using the False Positive Rate and the True Positive Rate, the highest was obtained by the K-NN model followed by the Decision Tree, and as stated earlier, the Naive Bayes had the worst score relatively.

But, when the same models were made to perform on the test data using the cross_val_score method, surprisingly, the Decision Tree performed the worst, with the Logistice Regressor and the Naive Bayes being the best two performers respectively. On conducting the statistical test, we found that the Logistic Regressor was the best model. However, on further scrutiny via the classification reports and the confusion matrices, we found that the Decision Tree had a better recall percentage than all other models. After which, considering the dynamics, we went ahead with the Decision Tree for deployment purposes.

Additionally, our neural network model, without any tuning process, had an accuracy of 88.13% on the train data, and as we tuned the hyper-parameters, we ended up with a final accuracy score of 88.91% approximately.

III. Conclusions¶

If we surf back to our Phase-1 report, we stated our objectives to be that, we intend to find out the best descriptive features that best decribe the target feature, and to predict if a customer would subscribe to a term deposit or not. In respect to the first point, from the phase-1 report itself, we were able to get an idea about the features that would best determine the target feature, and via using the Feature Selection methods in this report, we were able to know the top-10 features that do-so.

Considering the second stated objective, we now have a better idea as to who would subscribe to a term deposit, and how sound our results will be. On deployment, the Decision Tree Model would help us characterize if the client would or would not subscribe to a term deposit by the outputs of either 0 or 1, the former indicating a negative outcome, and the latter, a positive one.

On the whole, a cross validated score of 0.788 by the Decision Tree Model on the test-data provides a fairly good estimate on who would subscribe to a term deposit. Also considering the profit and loss of an organisation, like stated earlier, this report is in-terms for predicting an outcome for a business, a bank in our case, and revenue is a huge part for a successful run of any business. Our Decision Tree model was able to correclty identify more people who had subscribed to a term deposit even though its cross validation score was the lowest amongst all the conventional machine learning models, we had tried. In conclusion, we prefer to deploy the Decision Tree model for predicting who would susbscribe to a term deposit in a bank.
